column168: PTL DRIVER HAD PROBLEMS AT THE SCALE HOUSE IN UTAH. HE WAS OVERWEIGHT SO THE SCALE HOUSE ALLOWED THE DRIVER TO CONTINUE TO A LOCAL TRUCK STOP TO TRY AND GET LOAD CORRECT WEIGHT WISE. PTL NOTICED WHEN HE OPENED HIS TRAILER DOORS THAT ALL THE BARRELS HAD EXPANDED AND PRODUCT WAS SEEPING THROUGH VENT HOLES IN LIDS ONTO TOPS OF DRUMS. LOAD WAS TAKEN TO AN FMC DISTRIBUTION CENTER IN BLACK MOUNTAIN, NV. TO BE FIXED. PRODUCT EXPANDED DUE TO EXTREMELY HOT TEMPERATURES, THEREFORE DURING MOVEMENT THE PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT OF THE VENT HOLES. THE DISTRIBUTION CENTER DETERMINED THAT THE BARRELS HAD BEEN OVERFILLED. THEY ARE 55 GALLON DRUMS AND THEY WERE ONLY SUPPOSED TO HOLD 52 GALLONS. THE FMC DISTRIBUTION CENTER AIRED THE TRAILER OUT AND COOLED IT DOWN. ALL OF THE SMELL AND PRODUCT EVAPORATED. column168: I WAS DRIVING TRACTOR #58 AND BOX TRAILER #165 TO RECLAIMED ENERGY, DELIVERING DRUMS OF WASTE.  AS I LOOKED IN THE MIRROR I NOTICED THERE WAS SOMETHING LEAKING OUT OF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  I WAS APPROACHED EXIT #123, AND DECIDED TO PULL OFF INTO THE TRUCK STOP THERE TO CHECK IT OUT.  IT WAS AROUND 4:30 PM.  AS I LIFTED THE DOOR I COULD SEE THAT A DRUM WAS LEAKING.  IT WASN'T LEAKING A GREAT DEAL BUT ENOUGH TO CREATE A PUDDLE IN THE TRAILER AND A DRIBBLE OUT OF THE BACK.  THE DRUM WAS ON THE BACK ROW AND THE GENERATOR WAS "JACKSON PRESS" IN INDIANAPOLIS.  THE PRODUCT LEAKING FELT, LOOKED AND SMELLED LIKE A TYPE OF WATER BASED CLEANER.  AS I WAS CLEANING UP THE LEAKAGE WITH SOME RAGS, A POLICEMAN CAME UP AND ASKED WHAT WAS GOING ON.  HE THEN CALLED THE SPICELAND FIRE DEPT.  WHILE THEY AND THE SHERIFFS DEPT WERE ARRIVING.  I GOT AN OVERPACK FROM THE TRAILER AND GOT THE ABSORBENT AND RAGS FROM THE SPILL KIT.  AFTER I SPREAD THE ABSORBENT AND FORMED A BARRIER WITH THE SOCKS (JUST IN CASE).  THEY TOLD ME I HAD TO STAY BACK WHILE THEY DID THEIR JOBS.  I THE CALLED SUPERVISOR TO REPORT IT.  AFTER THEIR TRYING FOR QUITE SOME TIME TO REMOVE THE DRUM FROM THE TRAILER (UNSUCCESSFULLY) I WENT OVER TO THE GARAGE (AT THE TRUCK STOP)  AND ASKED TO USE SOME SCRAP TIRES STACKED AROUND BACK. I STACKED 4 SEMI TIRES AT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND PUSHED THE DRUM OVER ONTO THE TIRES.  THEN I HAD TWO OF THE FIREMAN TILT AND HOLD THE OVERPACK AGAINST THE TIRE. WHILE I PUSHED THE DRUM OVER AND INTO IT.  I BORROWED A BROOM FROM THE GARAGE CLEANED UP EVERYTHING AND PUT IT IN THE OVERPACK ALSO.  I THEN SEALED THE OVERPACK.  AFTER ALL OF THIS, A DOT OFFICER ARRIVED.  HE ASKED WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS.  I TOLD HIM THAT I HAD A LEAKING DRUM.  LOOKING AT THE OVER PACK, HE ASKED WHERE WAS IT LEAKING.  I TOLD HIM THAT THAT WAS AN OVERPACK. HE THEN LOOKED AROUND AND ASKED WHERE THE DRUM WAS.  I EXPLAINED TO HIM THAT THE DRUM WAS IN THE OVERPACK.  HE ASKED FOR THE MANIFEST AND ALL OF MY CREDENTIALS AND WENT BACK TO HIS CAR.  MEANWHILE THE FIRE DEPT & SHERIFF LEFT.  I THEN INTO THE TRUCKSTOP TO MAKE SOME PHONE CALLS TO FIGURE OUT HOW TO GET THE OVERPACK BACK INTO THE TRAILER.  AS I WAS SPEAKING TO STEVE MAHONEY, DENNIS BROWN CAME IN.  WE DECIDED TO CALL A TOW TRUCK SERVICE IN CAMBRIDGE CITY.  WHEN THEY ARRIVED WE WRAPPED THE CABLE AROUND THE DRUM AND LIFTED IT ONTO THE TRAILER.  WE SECURED THE LOAD AND THAT WAS THAT.  BY THEN THE DOT OFFICER WAS FINISHED.  HE ISSUED SEVERAL WARNINGS AND A TICKET FOR A LEAKING DRUM.  I THEN HEADED ON TO CONNERSVILLE, AT ABOUT 7:15 PM

column168: THE DRIVER CONNECTED ALL OF THE OFF-LOADING LINES TO THE CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK, THEN OPENED THE TRAILER DISCHARGE AND VAPOR RECOVERY VALVES.  WHEN HE OPENED THE VALVES AND TESTED FOR LEAKS HE NOTICED A SMALL LEAK AT THE PACKING GLAND OF THE FRONT LIQUID VALVE.  AT THIS POINT HE UNSUCCESSFULLY TRIED TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING GLAND OF THE VALVE WITH NO IMPROVEMENT.  HE THEN CLOSED THE VALVE, BUT THAT DID NOT STOP THE LEAK.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CHLORINE WAS BEING FED BACK FROM THE CUSTOMER ONLINE STORAGE TANKCAR INTO THE LIQUID VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK.  ALL TRUCK AND CUSTOMER VALVES WERE THEN SHUT.  THE DRIVER THEN PURGED THE LIQUID LINE INTO THE CAUSTIC SYSTEM ON HIS TRUCK HOPING THAT WOULD ALLOW HIM TO DISCONNECT, BUT THERE WAS TOO MUCH CHLORINE ALREADY IN THE LINE FROM THE CUSTOMER'S TANK TO SUCCESSFULLY PURGE OUT OF THE LINE.  AFTER DISCUSSING THE SITUATION WITH THE OPERATOR, THEY DECIDED TO PULL A VACUUM ON THE LIQUID LINE FROM THE CUSTOMER'S TANK SYSTEM TO CLEAR THE CHLORINE FROM THE LINE WHICH WOULD ALLOW THEM TO DISCONNECT.  WHEN THE LIQUID LINE INDICATED CLEAR AT THE CUSTOMER TANK SYSTEM MONITOR, THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO DISCONNECT THE LINE FITTINGS AND RECEIVED A MINOR EXPOSURE TO CHLORINE THAT WAS TILL IN THE LINE.  IT WAS FURTHER DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID LINE HAD A FROZEN PLUG OF ICE IN THE LINE THAT PREVENTED THE COMPLETE REMOVAL OF THE CHLORINE FROM THE LINE.  THIS ICE PLUG OCCURRED BECAUSE THE VACUUM PROCESS PRODUCES A NEGATIVE PRESSURE THAT ALLOWS THE CHLORINE TO AUTO-REFRIGERATED AND FREEZE IF THE PROCESS IS PERFORMED TOO QUICKLY.  THE OPERATOR PILLED ADDITIONAL VACUUM ON THE LINE FOR ANOTHER 30-45 MINUTES BEFORE HE AND THE DRIVER WERE ABLE TO DISCONNECT THE LINES.  THE CARGO TANK WAS RETURNED TO THE ALL-PURE FACILITY IN SANTA FE SPRINGS, CA AND THE DEFECTIVE VALVE WAS REPLACED ON THE TRAILER ON 8/11/98 AFTER THE TRAILER WAS EMPTIED AND PURGED.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO A MEDICAL PROFESSIONAL FOR OBSERVATION, THE DOCTOR FOUND NO INDICATIONS OF INJURY AND RELEASED THE DRIVER TO RETURN TO WORK THE NEXT DAY.  THE VALVES PACKING GLAND WAS OVER TIGHTENED, PROPERLY DURING THE LOADING PROCESS, AND THIS FAILED WHEN CONNECTED TO A LIVE SYSTEM AND THE VALVES WERE OPENED.  IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT IF A VALVE IS IDENTIFIED AS DEFECTIVE DURING LOADING IT SHOULD BE TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE AND REPLACED/REPAIRED IMMEDIATELY. IT IS ALSO RECOMMENDED THAT ALL DELIVERIES BE MADE TI ISOLATED SYSTEMS WITHOUT ANY CHANCE OF SYSTEM PRESSURE FEEDING BACK INTO THE TRUCK OFF-LOADING LINES.

column168: DRIVER STOPPED HIS TRUCK AT THE TOLL BOOTH AT EXIT 11, NJ TURNPIKE, AND THE REAR CLEANOUT CAP WAS KNOCKED OFF THE TOP OF THE TRAILER BY A SURGE OF PRODUCT. PRODUCT SLOSHED OUT OF THE OPEN CLEANOUT PORT AND RAN DOWN SIDES OF TRAILER.  THERE WAS A VERY STRONG ODOR OF ACETIC ACID, AND SOME OF THE FUMES CAUSED ONE OF THE TOLL TAKER PERSONNEL TO FEEL ILL EFFECTS.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL TREATED HER AT THE SCENE, AND SHE RETURNED TO HER JOB WITHOUT BEING REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP BY TURNPIKE AUTHORITIES.  THERE WERE NO OTHER INJURIES. NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAY.  INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT THE CLEANOUT CAP WAS LOOSE BECAUSE THE GASKET MATERIAL WAS MISSING FROM IT.

WHILE UNLOADING THE DRUM FROM THE TRAILER THE BOTTOM CHIME BEGAN TO LEAK.  THE LEAK ONLY OCCURRED AS THE DRUM WAS BEING MOVED.  THE CHIME WAS PLUGGED AND THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A 85 GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM FOR STORAGE PURPOSES UNTIL THE WASTE CAN BE PROCESSED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT SPILLS OF A SIMILAR NATURE, THE DRIVERS HAVE BEEN TOLD TO INSPECT THE DRUM INTEGRITY BEFORE THEY ACCEPT THE DRUM FOR SHIPMENT.  THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED OUT WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  APPROXIMATELY 5 POUNDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THIS WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED OF WITH THE REST OF THE FACILITY'S HAZARDOUS DEBRIS AT THE FACILITY AT SAFETY KLEEN SYSTEMS, 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TEXAS 76208.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF VIA INCINERATION.

THE MATERIAL WAS BEING STORED ON SITE AWAITING TRANSPORTATION TO THE FINAL TSDF WHEN A PIN HOLE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  THIS RELEASE WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS, CONTAINERIZED AND STORED ON SITE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THIS MATERIAL WILL BE SENT TO SAFETY KLEEN'S TSF LOCATED AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TEXAS 76208.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF VIA FUEL BLENDING.  TO PREVENT SPILLS LIKE THIS IN THE FUTURE THE DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CHECK ANY AND ALL DRUMS FROM INTEGRITY BEFORE SHIPMENT.

WHEN THE METAL TOTE WAS FILLED WITH THE WASTE NOT ENOUGH ROOM WAS LEFT INSIDE FOR EXPANSION DUE TO HEAT.  AS THE MATERIAL HEATED DURING THE DAY ONE PINT OF METHANOL AND DIMETHYLFORMAMIDE LEAKED OUT FROM THE TOP FITTING.  TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN, THE FACILITY WILL LEAVE ROOM IN THE CONTAINERS FOR EXPANSION. THIS RELEASED WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS, CONTAINERIZED AND STORED ON SITE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THIS MATERIAL WILL BE SENT TOO SAFETY-KLEEN'S TSF LOCATED AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TX 76208.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF VIA FUEL BLENDING.

THIS SPILL OCCURRED AS DRUMS WERE BEING UNLOADED FROM A TRUCK.   ONE OF THE DRUMS FELL OFF THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND SPILLED 1.5. GALLONS OF LIQUID UPON HITTING THE GROUND.  THE SPILL OCCURRED ON ASPHALT AND WAS ABSORBED WITH CORN COBBS AND ABSORBENT PADS WHICH WERE STORED FOR TRANSPORT AND PROCESSING AT A LATER DATE.  THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED OUT WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  APPROXIMATELY 5 POUNDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THIS WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED OF WITH THE REST OF THE FACILITY'S HAZARDOUS DEBRIS AT THE FACILITY AT SAFETY-KLEEN SYSTEMS, 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TX  76208. THE MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF VIA INCINERATION.  TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE THE FORKLIFT DRIVER AND OFF-LOADING CREW WERE ADVISED ON SAFE DRUM HANDLING.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Dropped; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: THIS SPILL OCCURRED WHEN THEY WERE LOADING A DRUM ONTO A TRAILER FOR SHIPMENT.  THE LOCK RING HANDLE BECAME LOOSE AFTER HITTING A PROTRUSION RESULTING IN THE DRUM FALLING OFF OF THE PALLET AND 15 GALLONS SPILLING INTO THE TRAILER BED.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, ABSORBED WITH CORN COBSAND ABSORBANT BOOMS AND PADS.  ONE (1) 30 GALLONS DRUM OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THIS WASTE WILL BE SENT TO SAFETY-KLEEN SYSTEMS, 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE, SE, HEBRON, OH  43025.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY FUEL BLENDING.  THE BRANCH MANAGER WILL RE-EMPHASIZE THE IMPORTANCE OF SAFE HANDLING DURING LOADING TO HIS EMPLOYEES.

WHILE A DRUM OF DRY CLEANING SOLVENTS WAS BEING LOADED ONTO A TRANSFER TRUCK, IT FELL OFF THE TRUCK AND RUPTURED THE TOP OF THE DRUM SPILLING THREE GALLONS OF TETRACHLOROETHYLENE ONTO THE CONCRETE.  THE LIQUID WAS CLEANED UP SITH SPILL PADS AND TRANSFERRED BACK TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN.  THIS FACILITY IS A PERMITTED TSDF.  THE WASTE, ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF CLEANUP MATERIAL, WILL BE INCINERATED.  TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE UNLOADING CREW WAS CANCELLED ON SAFE DRUM HANDLING.

A DRUM OF A COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID WAS BEING PUMPED INTO A STORAGE TANK AND THE MATERIAL SPILLED ON THE FLOOR DUE TO A DEFECTIVE HOSE.  ALL THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  APPROXIMATELY 50 POUNDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED. THIS CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A WASTE DRUM TO BE SHIPPED OUT TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 581 MILIKEN DRIVE. SE, HEBRON, OH  43028.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY INCINERATION.    TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS LIKE THIS IN THE FUTURE ALL THE HOSES AT THE FACILITY WILL BE INSPECTED.

THIS SPILL OCCURRED WHEN THE FACILITY WAS LOADING A 55 GALLON DRUM ONTO A TRUCK FOR SHIPMENT.  THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WAS RUSTED AND 8 OUNCES OF LIQUID SPILLED ONTO THE BED OF THE TRUCK.  THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH ONE ABSORBENT PAD AND OVERPACKED INTO AN 85 GALLON POLY DRUM ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED METAL DRUM.  THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF WASTE MADE WAS LESS THAN 5 POUNDS.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT ALL DRUMS FOR LEAKS BEFORE TRANSPORTING THEN IN THE FUTURE.  THE DRUM AND THE ABSORBENT PADS WILL BE SENT TO:SAFETY KLEEN SYSTEMS INC.  1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TX 76208.  THE METHOD OF DISPOSAL WILL BE FUEL BLENDING.

A DRUM OF ACETONE LOST ITS INTEGRITY AND SPILLED A SMALL AMOUNT OF WASTE ONTO THE GROUND OF THE TRANSFER FACILITY.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED WITH PADS AND CORN COB.  THE WASTE GENERATED, APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS, WAS PLACED ALONG WITH THE DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK FOR DISPOSAL.  THIS WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED AT SAFETY-KLEEN SYSTEM, 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TX  76208.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF VIA FUEL BLENDING. THE DELIVERY DRIVER HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED ON INSPECTING DRUMS PRIOR TO ACCEPTING THEM FOR TRANSPORT.

DRIVER PREPARED TO UNLOAD PRODUCT AND WHEN THE PROCESS INDICATED HE WAS TOP OPEN THE QRV (EXTERNAL VALVE), PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE STEM OF THE VALVE.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PROCESS AND CLOSED INTERNAL VALVE ON TRAILER.  CUSTOMER PERSONNEL PERFORMED CLEANUP OPERATION.  CARRIER CALLED IN OUTSIDE REPAIR VENDOR TO SERVICE THE DEFECTIVE QRV VALVE AT THE SITE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY.

AT APPROXIMATELY TEN MINUTES INTO THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE DELIVERY HOSE BURST AND CAUSED A SPILL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO PRODUT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS. PERSONNEL FROM THE CUSTOMER DIKED THE MATERIAL, NEUTRALIZED AND PACKED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: JIMMY CHAMBERS WAS WORKING A CITY UNIT. TR#9165 THAT PHIL HICKS BROGHT IN. HE WORKED IT ALL THE WAY TO THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER WHERE THE REAGENTS ACCT. WAS LOADED. HE WAS WORKING THIS AND NOTICED LIQUIDS ON THE FLOOR. HE SEEN THE BOX THAT WAS BUSTED SEEN THE LABEL ON THE SIDE THEN IMMEDIATELY CAME OUT OF THE TRAILER , PULLED THE DOOR DOWN AND CAME AND GOT ME,I CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE HAND WORK AND CALLED OUR SAFETY TEAM IN DOTHAN, WHERE I WAS CONTACTED WITH EDDIE YANCE. I THEN FOLLOWED ALL PROPER PROCEDURES. JIMMY USED RUBBER GLOVES AND EYE PROTECTION WHEN REMOVING THE BUSTED CONTAINER AND PUTTING DOWN ABSORBANT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE CHEMICAL EVAPORATED QUICKLY SO THE BOXES THAT WERE DAMP WITH THE SPILL WAS PLACED ON THE DOCK AND DRIED OUT BEFORE THEY WERE TRANSPORTED WILL ADVISE THE DRIVER TO USE EXTRA PERCAUTION WHEN LOADING HIS CITY UNIT EITH THIS LEAGENTS ACCOUNT.

THE DRIVER FINISHED WORKING ON A TANK OF OIL, OPENED THE VALVE TO THE TANK AND DID NOT NOTICED 1" VALVE TO EPA BOX WAS LEFT OPEN. WALKED OVER TO THE TRUCK TO START LOADING AND LOOKED OVER AND NOTICED EPA BOX RUNNING OVER RESULTING IN A TWENTY GALLON SPILL. NECESSARY CLEANUP WAS HANDLED.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENT LIKE THIS, SAFETY MEETING WAS CONDUCTED WITH ALL EMPLOYEES TO MAKE SURE THEY CHECK ALL VALVES BEFORE OPENING VALVE TO TANK.

column168: THE DRIVER OVERFILLED THE TANK TRAILER WHILE PICKING UP A LOAD AT THIS FACILITY.  HE DID NOT LEAVE ANY HEAD SPACE WHEN IT WAS FILLED. THIS VEHICLE HAS A VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM AS PART OF ITS EQUIPMENT. WHEN THE PARKING BRAKE IS APPLIED IT OPENS THIS SYSTEM UP.  SOME OF THE  WASTE SOLVENT FROM THE OVERFILLED TANK WENT INTO THIS SYSTEM. WHEN THE PARKING BRAKE IS RELEASED, THIS SYSTEM CLOSES AND RELEASES ANY VAPORS THAT HAVE ACCUMULATED.  BECAUSE OF THE ANGLE THE TRUCK WAS AT, AND THE FACT THAT THERE  WAS FREE LIQUID IN THIS SYSTEM, A RELEASE OCCURRED.  APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ROADWAY, THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND THE SEWER.  SAFETY-KLEEN HAD AN ER CONTRACTOR, TRADE WINDS, RESPOND TO THE SPILL TO MITIGATE THE SITUATION.  EIGHT 16 GALLON DRUMS OF ABSORBENT AND SOLVENT, THREE 55 GALLON DRUMS OF SOIL AND SOLVENT, AND EIGHT 55 GALLON DRUMS OF SOLVENT AND WATER WERE GENERATED FROM THE CLEAN UP.  THIS MATERIAL WILL BE SENT TO SAFETY-KLEEN'S PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 582 MILIKEN DRIVE SE, HEBRON, OH 43025.  THE MATERIAL WILL BE RECYCLED.   THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE NEW YORK STATE DEC.   THE CASE NUMBER IS 9806424.

EIGHT GALLONS WERE RELEASED WHEN THE LID POPPED OFF THE DRUM.  THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT PIGS.  EIGHTY PONDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THE WASTE WILL BE SHIPPED TO A SAFETY-KLEEN'S PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED A T 582 MILIKEN DRIVE SE HEBRON, OH 43025. THE WASTE WILL BE RECYCLED.  TO PREVENT SIMILAR INCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS GIVEN ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON MOVING FULL PALLETS.

THE WASTE WILL BE SENT TO SAFETY-KLEEN SYSTEMS, INC., 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TX  76208.  THE METHOD OF DISPOSAL WILL BE FUEL BLENDING/RECYCLING. column168: EIGHT OF EIGHT LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE MOUNTING FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE, GATX 57053, AUGUST 16, 1998, Philadelphia DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1015 HOURS, SUNDAY, AUGUST 16, 1998, AT CONRAIL'S ALLENTOWN YARD IN ALLENTOWN, PA A CONRAIL EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 50753 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED IT HAD EIGHT OF EIGHT LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE MOUNTING FLANGE BOLTS LOOSE.  THE BOLTS COULD NOT BE SECURED DURING INSPECTION.  ON AUGUST 17, 1998, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM REACT, AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY REACT WHO SECURED ALL EIGHT BOLTS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1020 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED, OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

ON AUGUST 28,1998 I WAS INSPECTING HB FULLER'S HAZ SHIPMENT WHEN NOTICED AN ODOR. I STOPPED INSPECTING AND LOOKED AT THE SHIPMENT MORE CLOSELY. THE BOX APPEARED TO HAVE ONCE BEEN WET & THEN DRIED. I LATER FOUND THAT THE SAME ODOR WAS NOTICED IN THE DRIVERS VAN. I CALLED OVER HAZ DEPT. & CHEMTRIC GOT THE MSDS, AND THE FOLLOWING DAY WALT STUNGAY FROM HB FULLER CAME WITH A DRUM  ON RECOVERED FROM OUTSIDE OUR BED, WHERE I PLACED IT. NO ONE WAS HURT DRIVER HAS RE-INSTRUCTED ABOUT HAZ SHIPMENT.
ARRIVED TO FIND SHIPMENT CRUSHED. SHIPMENT WAS DRUMMED, AND PLACED IN THE WASTE BUILDING AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPARTMENT. UNKNOWN CAUSE OF DAMAGE.

CONRAIL'S SENIOR TRAINMASTER AND GENERAL CAR FOREMAN ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT IT HAD A LOOSE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND A LOOSE BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVE. column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT CUSTOMER CONNECTED HIS HOSES FOR UNLOADING. PLACED A 5 - GALLON PAIL UNDER VALVE, OPENED/REMOVED DUST CAP, AND PRODUCT RAN OUT INTO PAIL AND ON DRIVEWAY. VALVE WAS IMMEDIATELY CLOSED BY UNLOADING PERSONNEL. DRIVER DID NOT CHECK UNLOADING VALVE FOR COMPLETE CLOSURE. WHICH IS STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE. CARGO TANK WAS COMPLETELY CHECKED AT OUR TERMINAL AFTER THIS INCIDENT, INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES WERE VACUUM TESTED TO ASCERTAIN THERE WERE NO MECHANICAL DEFECTS. NONE WERE FOUND. THIS INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY DRIVER ERROR. DRIVER HAS BEEN TERMINATED.

UTLX 42961 WAS FOUND TO LEAK PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN BALTIMORE, MD. THE CONSIGNEE, WHO WAS NEARBY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. THEY FOUND ONE OF THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WAS LOOSE. THE BOLT WAS MADE WRENCH TIGHT AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.

TANK CAR ACFX 75987 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING, AUG 4, 1998 FROM ITS TOP WHEN MOVED. T/C WAS ISOLATED. SHIPPER, NESTE RESINS CORP, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SITE. DURING THEIR INSPECTION OF THE T/C THEY FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE FAULTY AND REPLACED IT WITH A NEW ONE. T/C WAS COUPLED TO SEVERAL BUFFER CARS AND MOVED. T/C WAS SECURED AND READY FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

ON AUGUST 5, 1998 AT APPROXIMATELY 0430 HOURS CREW ON Q55605 WAS SWITCHING T/C GATX 61458 WHEN PRODUCT (VAPOR) WAS RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED THE CONSIGNEE. WHEN T/C WAS INSPECTED IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE AN IMPROPER DISC. IT HAD A BS & B TYPE SR-TC INSTEAD OF AN OSECO HCL-RC RUPTURED DISC. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. PROPER DISC WAS INSTALLED.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING AT PLACEDO STATION 00576. DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW WRITTEN PROCEDURE FOR UNLOADING, THEREFORE HE DID NOT HAND GAUGE TANK BEFORE UNLOADING. WHEN HE GOT UNLOADED, THE TANK WAS BRIM FUEL, AND 21 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL WAS RELEASED TO THE DIKE AREA THROUGH THE TANK OVERFLOW PIPE.

A DRUM OF WASTE PERCHLOROETHYLENE FELL OFF OF A PALLET WHILE BEING LOADED ONTO A TRUCK FOR SHIPMENT. TWO GALLONS SPILLED INTO THE TRUCK BED AND WAS ABSORBED WITH PADS. FIVE GALLONS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED AND WILL BE TRANSPORTED TO A PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE SE IN HEBRON,OH 43205 FOR RECYCLING. EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO SECURE ALL BARRELS ON PALLETS PRIOR TO MOVING THEM.

WHILE FILLING A DRUM WITH FLAMMABLE LIQUID THE DRUM WAS OVERFILLED TO THE POINT OF SPILLAGE. THE LIQUID WAS ABSORBED USING SPILL PADS AND TRANSFERRED BACK TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL. THE WASTE IS BEING TAKEN TO A PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD IN DENTON, TX 76208 FOR RECYCLING. TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER OVERFLOWS THE FACILITY WILL CONDUCT A TRAINING.

A STEP VAN BECAME ENGULFED IN FLAMES THAT ORIGINATED FROM THE ENGINE COMPARTMENT AND SPREAD TO THE REST OF THE VEHICLE. THE VAN WAS CARRYING A MIXED LOAD OF WASTE SOLVENT AND EXEMPT COMBUSTIBLE LIQUIDS. THERE WAS A TOTAL OF 56 GALLONS OF THE REGULATED WASTE SOLVENT AND 109 GALLONS OF THE EXEMPT COMBUSTIBLE LIQUIDS. ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO CONTAIN ANY SPILLED LIQUID. NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. ALL THE MATERIAL LEFT ON THE TRUCK AFTER THE FIRE WILL BE DISPOSED OF AS WASTE. THREE 55-GALLON DRUMS OF LIQUID SOLVENT WILL BE FUELS BLENDED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE, SE , HEBRON, OH 43025. ONE 30-GALLON DRUM OVERPACKED INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM WILL BE OVERPACKED AND SENT TO THE SAME TSDF FOR RECYCLING. FIVE 55 GALLON DRUMS OF SOLIDS WILL BE SENT TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 550 BLUESKY PARKWAY LEXINGTON, KY 40509 FOR FUELS BLENDING. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT IS CURRENTLY INVESTIGATING THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE IN THE ENGINE COMPARTMENT AND SAFETY-KLEEN WILL INSPECT ALL THEIR VEHICLES TO ENSURE THE SAME PROBLEM DOESN'T OCCUR. THERE WAS WASTE FROM THREE SEPARATE GENERATORS ON THE VAN AT THE TIME OF THE FIRE. THE SHIPPING PAPERS ARE ATTACHED.

WHILE OFF-LOADING A DRUM FROM A TRUCK THE DRUM FELL, THE LID WAS LOST, AND FOUR GALLONS OF SOLVENT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH PADS AND 60 POUNDS OF WASTE WAS GENERATED WHICH WILL BE TRANSFERRED TO PERMITTED TSDF LOCATED AT 550 BLUE SKY PARKWAY IN LEXINGTON, KY 40509 FOR RECYCLING. EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO SECURE DRUMS PRIOR TO OFF-LOADING TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.
WHILE UNLOADING, FORKLIFT ATTACHMENT STRUCK AND PUNCTURED A DRUM. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.
ONE PAIL WAS FOUND EMPTY WHEN UNLOADED. ALL SPILLAGE AND PAIL WERE NEUTRALIZED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.

# 1 HAD JUST LOADED AT THE ACETONE LOADING RACK AT THE TEXACO REFINERY IN EL DORADO, KS. THE GROSS GALLONS ON THE LOAD WAS 7500 GALLONS. # 1 HAD TO CROSS ONE SET OF RAILROAD TRACKS WHICH ARE INSIDE THE REFINERY. WHEN # 1 HAD CLEARED THE RAILROAD TRACKS AND PROCEEDED STRAIGHT, THE TRAILER CAME APART FROM THE TRACTOR. WHEN THE TWO UNITS SEPARATED THE TRAILER SLID BACK AND CAME TO REST ON THE FRAME RAILS ON THE TRACTOR. THIS CAUSED THE DOLLY LEGS TO HIT THE GROUND. WHEN THE DOLLY LEGS HIT THE GROUND A SUPPORT BRACKET BROKE AND WENT UP AND PUNCTURED A HOLE ON # 1 COMPARTMENT. THE PUNCTURE IS APPROXIMATELY THE SIZE OF A QUARTER. 192 GALLONS WERE LOST BEFORE PUNCTURE HOLE WAS SEALED OFF.

OF GUARD RAIL BEFORE FALLING OFF THE BRIDGE AND INTO THE CREEK. THE END OF THE TRAILER RIPPED OPEN AND THE PRODUCT IGNITED. THE DRIVER GOT OUT OF THE UNIT AND SUFFERED BURNS, BRUISES AND SCRAPES. THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL AND WAS KEPT FOR TWO DAYS. GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL WA CALLED TO COORDINATE THE CLEAN UP. THE CREEK WAS DAMMED UP AND PUMPED OUT. THE COWS HAD BEEN ALLOWED TO ROAM AND HAD NO MARKINGS TO IDENTIFY OWNERSHIP. APPROX. 5,000 BARRELS OF WASTE WATER WAS REMOVED.

DRIVER HAD UNLOADED CARGO PRIOR DAY AND HAD 20 PSI READING  ON PRESSURE GUAGE WHEN HE DEPARTED CONSIGNEE'S PLANT AT SUMMIT, ILLINOIS. AT 08:15 ON DAY OF INCIDENT, PRESSURE WAS 70 PSI-AT 11:05a.m., PRESSURE HAD REACHED 85 PSI. AUTOMATIC  RELIEF DEVICE IS SET FOR 90 PSI. DRIVER PULLED INTO HIGHWAY REST AREA WHERE THE D.O.T. WAS CONDUCTING MCSCAP INSPECTIONS, AND NOTIFIED THE OFFICIALS THAT TRAILER REQUIRED MANUAL VENTING UNDER CONTROLLED CIRCUMSTANCES. REST AREA WAS CLEARED OF INSPECTORS AND CIVILIANS, FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED IN, AND TRAILER WAS SUCCESSFULLY VENTED TO 10P.S.I. AND UNIT CONTINUED TO ORIGINAL SHIPPER LOCATION FOR INSPECTION AND CONTROL. SHIPPER SENT REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE OF THE PRESSURE RELEASE.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON I-71 WHEN THE DRIVER BEGAN TO HAVE DIFFICULTY CONTROLLING THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER STARTED TO SLOW AND MOVE TO THE BERM, HITTING THE GUARDRAIL AND STOPPING APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET LATER ON THE BERM. THE CAUSE OF THE LOSS OF CONTROL APPEARS TO BE THE RESULT OF THE TREAD ON THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE SEPARATING. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO BRING THE TRUCK TO A CONTROLLED STOP WITHOUT INVOLVING ANY OTHER VEHICLES OR ANY INJURIES. THE TRAILER CONTAINED SIX FULL PORTABLE TANKS OF BLEACH WHICH WERE SECURED WITH STRAPS BUT DUE TO THE JARRING NATURE OF HITTING THE GUARDRAIL, THE TANKS BOUNCED AND IT IS BELIEVED THAT ONE OF THE TANKS HIT THE VALVE OF THE OTHER TANK, CRACKING ITS VALVE OFF. THE TANK WITH THE BROKEN VALVE LEAKED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS (300 GALLONS). THE DRIVER PUT UP HIS EMERGENCY SIGNS, USED A SPILL CONTAINMENT KIT KEPT IN THE TRUCK TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER AND NOTIFIED LOCAL AUTHORITIES.

UPON ROUTINE LOAD INSPECTION DRIVER SAW MOISTURE INSIDE TRAILER. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED PERSONNEL TO THE SCENE. THERE WAS A PINHOLE THAT CAUSED THE LEAK.  CREW CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL; NONE ESCAPED ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DESIGNATED FACILITY HANDLED DISPOSAL OF SPILL DEBRIS.

UPON ROUTINE INSPECTION OF HIS LOAD, DRIVER NOTICED A DRIP FROM THE TRAILER.  HE PLACED A BUCKET UNDER TRAILER TO CATCH DRIP.   HE REPORTED SPILL TO COMPANY BUT AT THAT TIME SUSPECTED IT WAS WATER. COMPANY ADVISED DRIVER TO PUT ON PPE AND ENTER TRAILER.  BEFORE HE DID THIS, LOCAL FIRE DEPT., ARRIVED AND DETERMINED IT WAS SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  A CREW (PRIVATE CONTRACTOR) WAS SENT TO CLEAN IT UP AND THEY LOCATED ONE DRUM, NOT SODIUM HYDROXIDE, LEAKING.  DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND CREW CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL.  LESS THAN ONE GALLON ESCAPED ONTO THE GROUND.  DESIGNATED FACILITY HANDLED DISPOSAL OF SPILL DEBRIS.

DOCK MAN UNLOADING SKIDS IN FRONT OF DRUMS AND FORKS WENT THROUGH TOO FAR AND PUNCTURED ONE OF THREE DRUMS.  THE DOCK MAN SAW WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND IMMEDIATELY LAID THE DRUM ON IT'S SIDE.  HE THEN TOOK IT ACROSS THE DOCK AND MADE A SPOT TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  HE LAID THE DRUM ON A DRUM BUGGY OUTSIDE AND PATCHED THE LEAK.  THE PRODUCT LOSS WAS APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS.  THERE SHOULD HAVE BEEN PLYWOOD OR SOME OTHER TYPE OF DUNNAGE USED TO SEPARATE THE DRUMS FROM THE SKIDS.  THE DRUM WAS SEALED AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THE CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABELS IMPRINTED ON THE CARTONS.  PLASTIC COVERING WAS REMOVED REVEALING THE TWO CARTONS ON TOP OF THE CRATE WERE LAYING DOWN CONTRADICTORY TO THE ORIENTATION ARROWS PRINTED ON THE CARTONS.  ONE OF THE PAILS CONTAINED IN ONE OF THE CARTONS HAD LEAKED ABOUT ONE GALLON OF THE "B" COMPONENT OF THE RESIN ONTO MOST OF THE OTHER CARTONS.  THE BOTTOM LAYER OF THE CRATE WAS ALSO PACED LAYING DOWN WHILE THE MIDDLE LAYER WAS UPRIGHT AND PROPERLY STACKED. UPON OPENING THE REMAINING WET CARTONS IT WAS NOTICED THAT SIX OF THE OTHER CARTONS HAD SEEPED ONTO THE SHREDDED PAPER PACKING.  THE PLASTIC PAILS WERE REMOVED FROM THE CARTONS/PACKING, THE PAILS PLACED IN STEEL RECOVERY DRUMS (AFTER DETERMINATION MADE THAT THEY WERE NOT LEAKING) AND PREPARED FOR TRANSPORT TO THE ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE.  CORRECTED BILL OF LADING WAS PREPARED FOR TRANSIT.

A WELD CRACKED AT CARGO TANK SUMP AREA, DUE TO FAILURE OF A PIPING SECUREMENT CLAMP.  THE BROKEN CLAMP ALLOWED THE DISCHARGE PIPING TO FLEX WHILE THE CARGO TANK WAS IN TRANSIT, CAUSING UNUSUAL STRESS AT THE WELDED JOINT.  LESS THAN FIVE GALLONS OF LIQUID LEAKED FROM THE CRACK, WAS CONTAINED IN A PAIL WHILE THE ENTIRE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.  ALL OTHER CARGO TANKS INTO THE FLEET HAVE BEEN INSPECTED FOR SIGNS OF SIMILAR CLAMP FAILURES, WITH NONE FOUND.

Consolidate Waste Industries (EPA #cad983668583) was called to clean up and transport to Crosby and Overton (EPA #cad0028409019) for disposal.

Consignee would not accept damaged drum. Drum was placed in a metal overpak salvage drum and returned to Service Transport Inc. ( Algood, Tennessee facility) for disposal. The product will be disposed of by Laidlaw Environmental Services of Greenbriar, Tennessee.

During the loading process IMTT personnel overfilled the trailer. Overfill was caused by computer not shutting down pump. Entire spill was contained to the spill pit and cleaned up by IMTT. No injuries were involved.

Loaded trailer had been dropped at the branch location awaiting another driver to deliver load. A wash rack employee mistakenly thought that the trailer was dirty and proceeded to move trailer into wash bay. Without checking, the employee opened the valves which resulted in a spill. Approximately 8,500 pounds or 700 gallons of product was spilled into a separator tank. The product was drummed by branch personnel and disposed of properly. No injuries were involved. All personnel at the branch were required to attend a remedial training class held by the region safety manager on 8/27/98.

I NEVER RECEIVED A CALL BACK.  I LET APPROXIMATELY 90 MINUTES PASS BEFORE I CALLED THE DUTY OFFICER A SECOND TIME.  AT THAT POINT DIANA SAID SHE'D FAX THE INFO TO THE CASFO.  I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER WHO  ADMITTED THIS WAS A PERSONAL SHIPMENT AS HE WAS CHANGING DOMICILES.  AS HE IS IN THE HOTEL INDUSTRY AND DOES NO SHIPPING FOR A LIVING, HE HAS NO TRAINING. column62: Abrasion; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: (A & B) THE STAR TANKER WAS DRIVING EAST ON RT. 40. A PASSENGER VEHICLE AHEAD OF THE TANKER MOVED OVER TO THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY, WITHOUT SIGNALING, AND BEGAN TO SLOW DOWN. AS THE TANKER DRIVER APPROACHED AND BEGAN TO PASS THE PASSENGER VEHICLE, THE PASSENGER VEHICLE ABRUPTLY PULLED BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY IN FRONT OF THE TANKER, AGAIN WITHOUT SIGNALING . THE TANK DRIVER SWERVED TO THE LEFT TO AVOID THE CAR AND THEN HAD TO COUNTER STEER TO THE RIGHT IN ORDER TO STAY ON THE HIGHWAY. THE TANKER ROLLED OVER ONTO IT'S LEFT-HAND SIDE AND SLID ON THE HIGHWAY CAUSING THE CARGO TANK TRAILER TO CRACK AND RUPTURE. THE TERMINAL SUPERVISOR RECEIVED A CALL FROM ANOTHER CARRIER ABOUT THE INCIDENT. THE TERMINAL MANAGER WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THE NEW JERSEY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, BUREAU OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE WERE ALREADY ON SITE AND THE SCENE WAS STABILIZED. THE TERMINAL MANAGER CALLED CLEAN HARBORS TO RESPOND AND PROVIDE CLEAN UP AND REMEDIATION SERVICES. THE INCIDENT IS CURRENTLY UNDER INVESTIGATION. SAFETY MEETINGS HAVE BEEN HELD WITH ALL OF THE TERMINAL DRIVERS TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT AND RAISE AWARENESS.

HARRIS HAS AN ON SITE REMEDY CREW AND THEY PERFORMED THE CLEANUP.  CONTENTS OF BBL WERE PUMPED INTO ANOTHER BBL AT HARRIS DOCK.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIAL IS PRESENTLY IN A RECOVERY DRUM AT HARRIS SITE.  CHEMTREC WAS CALLED BY HARRIS PERSONNEL.  I AM CURRENTLY TRYING TO RECOVER DNG PLASTIC BBL FOR FURTHER EXAMINATION. PEDDLE DRIVER REPORTED HE HAD MADE A DELIVERY APPROXIMATELY HALF MILE FROM HARRIS AND BBL WAS NOT LEAKING AT THAT TIME.  SOME CONTENTS OF DMG BBL DRIPPED ON ASPHALT ROAD ADJACENT TO DOCK AND THIS WA ALSO NEUTRALIZED BY HARRIS CREW.  BBL WAS  HARRIS ON FRIDAY AND PUNCTURE APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY FORKLIFT BLADE.

DRIVER EASTBOUND ON ALGONQUIA STREET NEARING ENTRANCE RAMP FOR ILLINOIS 53.  THIS REQUIRES A LEFT HAND TURN AT A LIGHT CONTROLLED INTERSECTION.  AS DRIVER PEPPER NEARED THE CORNER AND BEGAN MAKING TURN, ANOTHER AUTOMOBILE CUT IN FRONT OF HIM, FORCING HIM TO BRAKE HARD.  WHEN THIS HAPPENED, THE DRUM TURNED OVER ONTO THE LIP OF A 2-WHEEL DOLLY CAUSING A GOUGE IN THE SIDE OF THE 55 GALLON DRUM.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL CALLED TO SCENE.  DRIVER IN THE MEANTIME HAD BREATHED SOME OF THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID FUMES SO HE WAS TRANSPORTED TO EMERGENCY WARD OF NEARBY HOSPITAL FOR EXAMINATION. HE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED WITHOUT FURTHER TREATMENT.  USF DUGAN IMMEDIATELY CONTRACTED OUR CONTRACTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY TO RESPOND. THE CONTRACTED VERGAN ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND OUT OF THE CICERO ILLINOIS AREA TO THE SCENE.  THEY ACCOMPLISHED THE CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER AND SMALL AREA OF THE RAMP WHICH DRIVER HAD PULLED OF ONTO.  STATE OF ILLINOIS DID MAKE A REPORT OF THE SPILL AND HAVE INDICATED THERE TO BE NO ENVIRONMENTAL CONTAMINATION AS RESULT OF SPILL. DRIVER WILL RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS OPERATOR ERROR.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURED. THIS PACKAGE HAD BEEN PICKED UP BY A COURIER OUT OF A FEDEX DROP BOX IN THE FT. WAYNE AREA. THE COURIER WAS TAKING THE PACKAGE OUT OF HIS VEHICLE WHEN IT APPARENTLY PARTIALLY EXPLODED. FEDEX MANAGEMENT AND DG PERSONNEL ON THE SCENE INDICATED THAT THE INNER UNIT APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN GIFT WRAPPED WITH WIRES COMING FROM THE DEVICE. THEY ALSO INDICATED THAT THERE APPEARED TO BE SOME TYPE OF OXIZED POWDER COMING OUT OF THE PACKAGE AS WELL. THE FORT WAYNE POLICE DEPARTMENT BOMB DISPOSAL UNIT WAS CALLED TO SECURE THE SITUATION AND MAKE  A DETERMINATION AS TO WHAT HAD OCCURED. THIS PROCESS TOOK APPROXIMATELY  TWO TWO HOURS TO COMPLETE. IN SPEAKING LATER WITH DETECTIVE COLIN BENDER OF THE FT. WAYNE BOMB SQUAD IT WAS HIS OPINION THAT THIS WAS SOME TYPE OF HOMEMADE EXPLOSIVE DEVICE. HE INDICATED THAT ONLY PART OF THE DETONATING  DEVICE HAD INITIATED AND THAT THERE WAS STILL SOME TYPE OF EXPLOSIVE LEFT IN THE PACKAGE. HE INDICATED THAT THEY WOULD BE REMOVING THE DEVICE FROM FEDEX PREMISES AND WOULD FINISHING DETONATING THE DEVICE FOR DISPOSAL. THEY ALSO INDICATED THAT THEY WOULD BE IN TOUCH WITH THE AFFECTED REGULATORY AGENCIES F.B.I. ATF ETC. PER 49CFR 171.15 I NOTIFIED SPECIAL AGENT ANDY HUBER OF THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION'S INDIANAPOLIS CIVIL AVIATION SECURITY FIELD OFFICE AND APRISED HIM OF THE SITUATION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: Regional Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, Dean L. Whitely, Sparks, NV., and Manager Environmental Field Operation Allen Jensen, Salt Lake City, UT., while making regulatory compliance inspections, Union Pacific Sparks yard, Sparks, NV., noted the odor of liquified petroleum gas around the protective housing of tank car CPDX 84354. Removed seal SOCAL A-1001 from securement pin hinged lid protective housing and inspection revealed vapor release from packing gland nut located on the slip tube gauging device. Packing gland nut was tightened which stopped vapor release. Chemtrec Jeff Botwinick was furnished details by RMCC, St. Louis, MO. Seal UPF-329850 was applied for protection.

Mgr., CTS, Larry Wilder was notified by RMCC at 0124 am on 8/18/98, that trailer EKLU 26093 was leaking unknown product. Mgr. Wilder found that a 55 gallon drum had a small hole in the top of the drum due to improper blocking and bracing. The shipper was called and a joint inspection was conducted along g with Kirk Jacobson, Mgr. damage prevention. The shipper agreed that the load was improperly blocked and braced. Heritage Environmental was called by the shipper and the trailer was transloaded into trailer KLFU 112500 on 8/19/98. Approximately one cup of product spilled onto the ground and this was cleaned up by Mgr. Wilder. No waterway, drains or other environmental issues involved. The rings on doorway drums showed evidence of rotation which resulted in the release of product. The shipper Mr. Sri Mosur of Austin stated that the load was acceptable to India's standards. Mgr. Wilder informed Mr. Mosur that this was not acceptable in the USA. Eight inch plywood veneer was used for the riser, drums were in a 2/3 pattern with a green rope used for blocking and bracing. The trailer also had improperly applied placards.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ON 8/27/98 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT SETTEGAST YARD. REPORTS FROM OBSERVERS SAID THAT THE CAR STARTED MAKING A SLIGHT HISSING SOUND THAT GREW INTO A ROAR. THEY COULD ALSO SEE A WHITE CLOUD AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND WHAT THEY THOUGHT WAS ICE FORMING ON THE HOUSING. REEDER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND EVIDENCE OF ICE ON THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE PRESSURE RATING ON THE VALVE WAS 300 PSI. PRESSURE IN THE CAR WAS 280 PSI. REEDER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND ASKED THAT THEY LOCATE A TANK TRUCK TO OFF LOAD ABOUT 1,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. WHILE WAITING, THE SAFETY VALVE VENTED TWICE. EACH EVENT LASTED ABOUT SEVEN MINUTES WITH ABOUT ONE HOUR BETWEEN EVENTS. THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WAS REQUESTED TO COME TO THE SITE FOR STANDBY. THE SHIPPER PROVIDED A TANK TRUCK THAT ARRIVED ABOUT 3:30 PM. AFTER HOOKING UP THE HOSES, GROUNDING AND BONDING THE VEHICLES, THE TRANSFER BEGAN. ABOUT 1,800 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS REMOVED BEFORE THE PRESSURE IN THE TWO TANKS EQUALIZED. THE ALL CLEAR WAS GIVEN AT 4:25 PM. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

MANAGER RODABOUGH RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM RMCC THAT ROY CITY POLICE RECEIVED A CITIZEN REPORT OF A CHEMICAL SMELL COMING FROM SOME TANK CARS BEHIND THEIR HOME. INSPECTION REVEALED FOUR OF FIVE CARS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY COVERS. ALL CARS WERE RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED MTBE. ALL OF THE CARS HAD MANWAY COVER BOLTS THAT WERE FINGER TIGHT. DUE TO HIGH TEMPERATURES IN THE AREA AND THE FACT THAT THE CARS ARE BLACK IN COLOR THEY HAD ALL PRESSURIZED AND WERE ALL VENTING. MANAGER RODABOUGH SECURED ALL MANWAY COVERS. ALL CARS WERE CHECKED FOR FURTHER LEAKS AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE POLICE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE COMPLAINANT, MRS. YEVONNE FALKNER OF 3733 SOUTH 2100 WEST ROY UT. CHEMTREC MR CHRIS YOUNG TOOK THE REPORT AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 75495. THE SHIPPER, PHILLIPS 66 AND THE CONSIGNEE, COASTAL CHEMICAL WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.

INSPECTION REVEALED THAT MANWAY GASKET WAS CRACKED. IT WAS REPLACED WITH GOR-TEX GASKET MATERIAL, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. REMOVED SEAL CAUSTIC BEFORE REPAIR, AFTER REPAIR APPLIED SEAL EMG-003595. REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, H.L. BART WAS NOTIFIED AT 1900 HOURS OF A LEAKING TANK CAR GATX 93931 AT CLINTO DRIVE IN GALENA PARK, TX. column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C.COOPER , MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS ADVISED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE CITY OF CALEXICO, CALIFORNIA.THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD RECEIVED THE REPORT FROM A CITIZEN THAT LIVES ADJACENT TO THE AREA OF CESAR CHAVEZ AND GRANT STREET,WHO WAS SMELLING THE ODORS. THIS AREA IS THE RAILROADS INTERCHANGE TRACKAGE FOR LPG CARS CROSSING OVER INTO MEXICO. THE CALEXICO FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE ON TANK CAR GATX29124. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT APPLIED A WATER SPRAY OVER THE TANK CAR ATTEMPTING TO COOL THE CONTENTS. AMBIENT TEMPERATURE IN CALEXICO HAVE BEEN WELL OVER 100 DEGREES FOR SOME TIME., AND IT APPEARED THE HEAT WAS EFFECTING THE PROPANE CONTENTS. WATER WAS APPLIED OVER THE TANK CAR FROM 2130 HOURS TO 2330. FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND FOUND IT HAD RESET AND WAS NO LONGER VENTING. MANAGER COOPER ARRIVED 0200 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 5,1998, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND NO LEAKS. UPON PLACING A PRESSURE GAUGE ON THE GAUGING ROD VALVE ASSEMBLY, THE INTERIOR PRESSURE REGISTERED AT 200 POUNDS. AS THE SAFETY VALVE IS SET FOR 280.5 POUNDS, IT WAS DETERMINED THE SRV WAS OPERATING WELL BELOW IT'S NORMAL SETTING SINCE THE PRODUCT PRESSURE WOULD NOT DROP 80 POUNDS IN LESS THAN 3 HOURS. AT 0600 HOURS, MET MR.JUAN MANUAL PEREZ, WHO RECEIVES THIS PRODUCT FOR TG&O. AFTER EXPLAINING THE CONDITION OF THE CAR, HE ARRANGED TO HAVE THE CAR DIVERTED TO THE GAS SILZA S.A.DE. MEXICALI FACILITY, WHERE IT COULD BE OFF LOADED. THIS WOULD EXPEDITE THE OFF LOADING OF THE PRODUCT, RATHER THAN HAVE THE CAR CONTINUE ON TO IT'S DESTINATION IN BAJA, MEXICO. AT  0730 HOURS, THE INTERCHANGE WAS COMPLETED FOR MOVEMENT INTO MEXICO, AND THE CAR WAS SET TO THE MEXICALI FACILITY BY 0900 HOURS WITHOUT INCIDENT. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH TG&O, NASSAU,BAHAMAS, WHO WAS ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE TANK CAR. TG&O PROVIDED A BILL OF LADING WHICH SHOWED THE VOLUME QT 28,518 GALLONS, WHICH COMPLIED WITH THE EMBARGO REQUIREMENTS,. SINCE TG&O WAS THE LESSEE OF THE CAR, THEY WOULD HAVE TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CAR SHOPPED UPON IT,S RETURN FROM MEXICO. THE SRV WOULD HAVE TO BE BENCH TESTED TO DETERMINE WHAT SETTING THE VALVE FAILED AT PRIOR TO PLACING THE CAR BACK INTO SERVICE.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUT BOUND PACKAGE SORT AND RELOAD OPERATION WHEN THE LEAKAGE /ODOR WAS NOTICED. HANDLING PERSONNEL ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED THE PACKAGE AND THIS REVEALED AN PLASTIC BOTTLE WHOSE CAP SEAL APPARENTLY FAILED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE IN BOUND SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE SHIPMENT HAD COME IN FROM MEXICO AND HAD BEEN TAKEN OVER TO THE U.S. CUSTOMS OFFICE FOR PROCESSING. WHILE THERE THE APPARENTLY INITIATED AND PARTIALLY INFLATED. THERE WAS NO SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT NOR WERE THERE ANY HAZ MAT MARKINGS TO SPEAK OF EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER CONTAINER. THE PACKAGE HAD THE CLASS 9 LABELS EXHIBITED BUT SOMEONE HAD GONE THROUGH SOME LENGTHS TO COVER THEM UP. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

column58: Basic Material; Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: THIS PACKAGE AND TWO OTHERS,  WERE DELIVERED TO THE WRONG ADDRESS AND THE CONSIGNEE CALLED TO REPORT THIS DELIVERY ERROR. COURIER/SPILL CLEAN UP AGENT JOSE ESPIRICUETA,  WENT TO PICK THESE PACKAGES UP AS ONE PACKAGE WAS REPORTED TO HAVE LEAKED WHILE AT THIS RESIDENCE. CONTENTS WERE OBSERVED TO BE POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS THAT HAD BEEN RE PACKED. THE BOXES IN QUESTION WERE NOT LABELED OR MARKED AS DANGEROUS GOODS.  CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE STATION.  I WAS CONTACTED BY STATION MANAGEMENT OF THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.  I CALLED THE SHIPPER TO REQUEST A MSDS,  SO THE PRODUCT COULD BE PROPERLY IDENTIFIED. THE PACKING LIST STATED IT WAS PRINTING INK AND METHANOL,  UN1210 AND UN1230. IT WAS DISCOVERED DURING CONVERSATIONS WITH THE SHIPPER, THAT THIS SHIPMENT HAD BEEN SHIPPED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCT TO HIS MCALLEN, TX. ADDRESS, AND THEN TRANSPORTED TO THEIR OFFICE IN MEXICO.  HOWEVER,  IT WAS THE INCORRECT PRODUCT, AND THE MEXICO OFFICE RETURNED THIS IN SEVERAL FIBERBOARD BOXES WITH NO MARKING, LABELING OR ANY DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION PAPERWORK. SHIPMENT SHOULD HAVE BEEN RETURNED TO ELK GROVE VILLAGE, IL. DUE TO THE RE PACKING, THE PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE NOT LOADED UPRIGHT,  AND THE PRODUCT LEAKED AROUND THE CLOSURE. THE OTHER TWO PACKAGES IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE AB# 4122-3558-4310. I CALLED THE SOUTHWEST REGION FAA DUTY OFFICE TO REPORT THIS UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.  JOHNNY EASON OF THE HOUSTON FAA OFFICE,  WAS TO INVESTIGATE.

column168: FILE AB03698, SHPR; RICK PAUL, ABW # GWD 8855739185 ATL, THIS IS A 5800.1F REPORT ONLY. ON 08/15/1998 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC.,  145 HUNTER DR WILMINGTON,  OH. AT 1400 HOURS H.L. BART AND GEOFFREY REEDER WERE NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT PIERCE YARD BY CAPT. TOMMY ERICKSON, HOUSTON HAZMAT.  BART AND REEDER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE, ARRIVING AT 1430 HRS AND FOUND TANK CAR UTLX 42470 VENTING THROUGH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  PRODUCT TEMPERATURE WAS TAKEN WITH AN INFRARED SENSOR, SHOWING 148 DEGREES F.  CONFIRMED PRODUCT WAS POLYMERIZING. S. A. D. T. FOR PRODUCT IS ACCORDING TO SHIPPER 140 DEGREES F.  BART MADE ENTRY WITH BACKUP PERSONNEL FROM HFD IN LEVEL A AT 1500 HRS TO FURHTER VENT CAR THROUGH AIR LINE TO PREVENT OVER PRESSURIZED AND POSSIBLE RUPTURE.  AT 1530 HOURS SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS PLUGGED BY PRODUCT POLYMERIZATON AND ANOTHER ENTRY WAS MADE TO VENT CAR VIA THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  AT 1630 HOURS FOUR(4) BOLTS WERE LOOSENED ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE TO ALLOW SUFFICIENT VENT CAPACITY TO PREVENT OVERPRESSURIZATION OF TANKCAR.  AT 1900 HRS PRODUCT TEMPERATURE WAS 93 DEGREES F AND PRESSURE HAD DROPPED SUFFICIENTLY TO ALLOW THE MANWAY PLATE TO BE FULLY OPENED. INSPECTION AT 1950 HOURS REVEALED REACTION HAD SUBSIDED AND POLYMERIZATION HAD FULLY OCCURRED.  ONE THOUSAND (1000) GALLONS OF WATER WAS ADDED TO THE POLYMERIZED PRODUCT TO COOL HOT SPOTS AND CAR WAS SECURED.  INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED AT 2030 HOURS, EVACUATION LIFTED AT 2045 HOURS AND DECONTAMINATION COMPLETED AT 2230 HOURS.

ON 08-20-98, UTLX 99216, LD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS ON STORAGE TRACK AT  DEGUSSA CORP IN THEODORE, AL, WHEN IT VENTED VAPORS FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. column168: Driver was off-loading unleaded gasoline into a remote fill location when the cap for the main fill riser (unleaded tank) came off resulting in a release of approximately 15 gallons of gasoline. The gasoline which spilled onto the ground migrated off site and into the street, but was contained prior to migrating into a storm drain. Once contained, the driver used absorbent powder material (provided by the station) to clean up the gasoline. The absorbent material and spill pads used during the clean up effort were returned to the distribution terminal for proper disposal. Driver was counseled on proper loading and unloading procedures. It should be noted that the Anaheim Fire Department responded to the spill scene. They were satisfied with the clean up efforts and no Department actions were taken.

CHECKED BAGGAGE WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM ALASKA AIRLINES FLIGHT 68 (SEA/JNU) TO FLIGHT 61 (JNU/CDV) ON 8/28/98.  THE RAMP EMPLOYEE NOTICED A STRONG ODOR OF SULFUR WHILE HE WAS IN THE CARGO PIT.  A SEARCH WAS CONDUCTED FOR THE SOURCE AND IT WAS EMANATING FROM A GREEN COLORED CANVAS BAG.  THE BAG WAS REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND OPENED.  A STANDARD FACTORY BOX OF STRIKE ANYWHERE MATCHES HAD IGNITED AND BURNED A TOWEL WHICH WAS ON TOP OF THE BOX OF MATCHES. THE FLAME HAD SELF-EXTINGUISHED.  IN THE CANVAS BAS ALONG WITH THE MATCHES WAS BOX OF FIRE STARTER STICKS.  THE OWNER OF THE BAG, DR. JAY ZUROFF WAS ONE OF A GROUP (11 PASSENGERS) ON A FISHING TRIP TO CORDOVA, ALASKA.  THE BAG TAG HAD A NAME OF ANOTHER PASSENGER FROM THE GROUP.  DR. ZUROFF IDENTIFIED THE BAG AS HIS. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE FAA FLIGHT STANDARDS OFFICE IN JUNEAU, ALASKA.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS INSPECTED PRIOR TO BEING PLACED IN SERVICE.

WE RECEIVED A CALL FROM CLARK MCEACHERN AT 9:50 A.M. HE ADVISED THAT THE CARBON DIOXIDE STORAGE TANK IN THE BUILDING HAD SPRUNG A LEAK. THE CARBON DIOXIDE WAS COMING OUT SO FAST THAT THEY WERE UNABLE TO DETERMINE WHERE IT WAS COMING FROM.  EVERYONE IN OUR BUILDING WAS EVACUATED AND ACCOUNTED FOR, AND SURROUNDING BUILDINGS WERE ALSO EVACUATED.   I ASKED CLARK IF HE COULD GO TO THE BACK OF THE BUILDING AND OPEN THE REAR DOOR TO VENTILATE THE BUILDING.  HE SAID THAT THE CARBON DIOXIDE WAS COMING OUT SO FAST THAT HE WAS CONCERNED ABOUT GOING BACK THERE.  I TOLD CLARK TO CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND ADVISE THEM OF THE SITUATION.  I GOT RENO ON THE OTHER PHONE LINE AND INFORMED HIM OF THE SITUATION.  WE DISCUSSED WHERE THE LEAK COULD BE COMING FROM.  CLARK SAID THAT HE HAD JUST FINISHED FILLING THE BULK TRUCK AND HAD DISCONNECTED FROM THE HOSE, THEN PULLED THE TRUCK OUT OF THE BUILDING.  CHRIS WAS IN THE BUILDING FILLING CYLINDERS, WHEN THIS OCCURRED.  HE RAN OUT OF THE BUILDING THROUGH THE FRONT DOOR.  I TOLD CLARK TO ADDRESS THE ISSUE OF THE LEAK, MAKE SURE EVERYONE WAS SAFE, ASSIST THE FIRE DEPT WHEN THEY ARRIVED, DIRECT ALL INQUIRES FOR INFORMATION FROM ANYONE OTHER THAN FIRE OR POLICE PERSONNEL TO ME.  ALSO TO CALL ME BACK IN FIFTEEN MINUTES WITH AN UPDATE ON THE SITUATION THERE.  AT 10:00 A.M., I CALLED THE MOBILE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SPOKE TO EVERETT MILLER TO ADVISE THEIR HAZMAT UNIT OF THE LEAK.  AT 10:17, CLARK CALLED FROM THE MOBILE DEPOT TO SAY TREATED THE LEAK HAD BEEN SHUT OFF, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS THERE AND THEY WERE FILLING OUT PAPERWORK.  CLARK STATED THAT THE LEAK HAD COME FROM THE SUPPLY PIPE TO THE SPEED PUMP.  CLARK FURTHER STATED THAT HE WAS DRIVING THE BULK TRUCK OUT OF THE DEPORT, WHEN UNBEKNOWNST TO HIM THE SIDE GATE FROM HIS TRUCK FELL DOWN AND CAUGHT THE FILL HOSE FROM THE SPEED PUMP.  THIS CAUSED THE HOSE TO BECOME ENTANGLED IN THE REAR WHEELS OF THE TRUCK AND THIS PULLED ON THE HOSE WHICH PULLED ON THE SPEED PUMP, WHICH PULLED ON THE 1 1/2 SUPPLY PIPE FROM THE RECEIVER TO THE SPEED PUMP AND BROKE THE PIPE. WE HAVE SPOKEN TO BOC ON SITE AT THE MOBILE DEPOT.  THE PRESSURE IN THE RECEIVER WAS 200 PSI.  BOC WILL FILL THE RECEIVER FOR US TODAY AND HAVE ONE OF THEIR SERVICE TECH'S MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE SYSTEM.  WE HAVE ADVISED THE DEPOT TO ENSURE THAT THE FILL HOSES ARE PROPERLY STORED WHEN LOADING HAS BEEN COMPLETED.  ALSO TO PERFORM A THOROUGH WALK AROUND OF THE TRUCK PRIOR TO DRIVING OUT OF THE DEPOT.
